description:
The Office of Student Affairs is pleased to announce Reed Smith's Virtual Law Student Mental Health Summit, an event designed to proactively address the mental health of aspiring lawyers. Speaker: Jordana Confino/Fordham Law School. Lawyers and law students tend to be strivers by both nature and nurture. We set lofty goals and work fastidiously to meet them, certain that achieving “success” will bring us satisfaction. But science shows that this logic is backward. Although we believe success will lead to happiness, the reality is that well-being fuels success and the key building blocks for well-being are not necessarily what you might think. In this session, you will: . . Learn to apply evidence-backed insights and techniques from positive psychology (the science of human flourishing) to effectively manage stress and enhance your personal and professional satisfaction.. . Explore the six elements of the PERMA-V model of well-being (Positive Emotions, Engagement, Relationships, Beaning, Achievement and Vitality) and learn strategies for increasing your experience of each element.. . Walk away with a toolkit of exercises and an action plan for pursuing your own authentic vision of success. . Register here: https://events.zoom.us/ev/Ap_3Yhbhi9mynI9NfTNBukfEtSnZ7uDx1Sgls1sLwboYdH9sj2ID~AggLXsr32QYFjq8BlYLZ5I06Dg

Meeting Link: https://events.zoom.us/ev/Ap_3Yhbhi9mynI9NfTNBukfEtSnZ7uDx1Sgls1sLwboYdH9sj2ID~AggLXsr32QYFjq8BlYLZ5I06Dg
---
Event Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377624
location: Online Event
summary: Law Student Mental Health Summit | Session 1: Foundations for flourishing. Leveraging the science of positive psychology to maximize well-being, resilience, and performance.

description:
The office of Student Affairs is pleased to announce Reed Smith's Virtual Law Student Mental Health Summit, an event designed to proactively address the mental health of aspiring lawyers. Speakers: Dr. Deborah Austin/University of Denver, and David Jaffe/American University Washington College of Law. While partaking might bring temporary relief from the stress of law school, or just seem “fun,” the effects of excessive alcohol and substance consumption can temporarily or permanently affect your brain just when you need it most. From cognitive function to the ability to take in and retain new information and overall brain health, the reality is that alcohol and substance use have an impact on your brain’s ability to work at full capacity. After the euphoria and through the haze of the day after, there are changes within the brain that you should know about as they can. . affect you during law school, in your future career and throughout your life.

Meeting Link:  https://events.zoom.us/ev/Ap_3Yhbhi9mynI9NfTNBukfEtSnZ7uDx1Sgls1sLwboYdH9sj2ID~AggLXsr32QYFjq8BlYLZ5I06Dg
---
Event Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377625
location: Online Event
summary: Law Student Mental Health Summit | Session 2: Through the haze: Impacts of alcohol and substance use on the law student mind.

description:
The Office of Student Affairs is pleased to announce Reed Smith's Virtual Law Student Mental Health Summit, an event designed to proactively address the mental health of aspiring lawyers. Speakers: Janet Stearns/Miami Law School, Taylor Davis/Reed Smith, . . Sarah Wilkinson/Reed Smith, and Voirrey Blount/Anglee Kumar. Law school is a high-stress environment that can take its toll on your mental health. It’s important to be honest with yourself and people in your life about how you are feeling. In this panel discussion, hear from current associates about how they maintained and prioritized their mental health during law school and/or sought support when needed. Our panel will also address the following key questions: How and when do we ask prospective employers about support for mental health and wellness in the process of applying and interviewing for jobs? How will firms respond to these types of concerns in our current era? How will bar examiners consider mental health concerns in evaluating character and fitness to practice law?

Meeting Link: https://events.zoom.us/ev/Ap_3Yhbhi9mynI9NfTNBukfEtSnZ7uDx1Sgls1sLwboYdH9sj2ID~AggLXsr32QYFjq8BlYLZ5I06Dg

The Office of Student Affairs is  pleased to announce Reed Smith's Virtual Law Student Mental Health Summit, an event designed to proactively address the mental health of aspiring lawyers. description:

The goal is to create awareness and understanding among participants of the detrimental effects of discrimination on the mental well-being of these student populations. description: Social Impact Marketing: The Essential Guide for Changemakers. . . . Join us for a lecture on leveraging your college experience as a platform for creating meaningful social impact. Whether you're a budding entrepreneur, a future humanitarian, or an artist with a passion for change, this lecture will provide you with valuable insights into how marketing can help expand your reach and influence. Using examples from corporate as well as nonprofit organizations, Professor Kulkarni will share how the intentionality in the marketing industry of today is helping drive consumer behavior around sustainability and social change. . . . . Maddy Kulkarni is a passionate marketing leader whose career has spanned corporate, nonprofit, and academic sectors. She has spent over 13 years as a leader in sustainability & marketing at PepsiCo, is the Founder and Executive Director of Dallas Heroes Project, a nonprofit organization, and is currently an adjunct professor at SMU. As the author of the textbook, Social Impact Marketing: The Essential Guide for Changemakers, she explains how marketing can be used to drive both business and social impact. Maddy serves on the Advisory Board of Sustainable Brands, a global industry organization that seeks to advance sustainability in business. She was also PepsiCo’s liaison to the World Federation of Advertisers and has spoken on behalf of the organization at the United Nations Global Compact’s Leaders Summit. Maddy has served on numerous non-profit boards and has been awarded a 40 Under 40 designation by Dallas Business Journal.  . . \n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377738
location: Moody Graduate Hall Auditorium, ,
summary: Sustainability & Marketing: Gartner Lecture Series feat. Professor Maddy Kulkarni

Brandon Coleman brings extensive, award-winning experience to his new role with the TGI Fridays brand. He joined the company in October 2022 and led the domestic corporate and franchise stores, as well as the TGI Fridays brand, as U.S. President and Chief Marketing Officer. Previously, Brandon had a successful career in the restaurant industry, serving as Senior Vice President and CMO of Dave & Busters, various leadership roles at Del Frisco's Restaurant Group, and as Chief Marketing Officer of Romano's Macaroni Grill. He also served as CEO and Management Consultant for Brava Partners, a consulting group focused on branding and business strategy. In 2013, Mr. Coleman was named one of Ad Age's 40 Under 40.. . \t. . TGI Fridays, the world's first casual bar and grill, operates and franchises over 650 restaurants across 52 countries. The company saw total system-wide sales of $1.6 billion in 2022, with U.S. sales growing at +8% compared to 2019 (pre-pandemic). The company announced its most significant deal in September of last year, consisting of 75 new franchised restaurants to be opened throughout South and Southeast Asia over the next 10 years representing an additional $500 million in restaurant revenue.\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377842

Workshop Highlights:. . - Choosing the Right Legal Entity: Discover the various legal structures available to startups and understand which one best aligns with your business goals.. . - Funding Strategies: Gain valuable insights into different funding options, from bootstrapping and angel investors to venture capital and crowdfunding.. . - Real-World Examples: Jim will draw on his extensive experience and real-world case studies to illustrate key concepts and best practices.. . . . Who Should Attend?. . This workshop is ideal for aspiring and early-stage entrepreneurs looking to establish a solid legal foundation for their startups and explore effective funding avenues. Whether you're launching a tech startup or a local small business, Founding and Funding will provide you with valuable insights to kickstart your entrepreneurial journey.. . . . Don't miss this opportunity to learn from a seasoned expert and take your startup to the next level. Join us for an engaging session that will equip you with the knowledge and strategies you need to succeed in the competitive world of entrepreneurship.. . . . About our Awesome Seminar Leader Jim Chester:. . With over 25 years of experience, Jim Chester is a seasoned legal professional and entrepreneur. He offers strategic legal counsel to innovators, specializing in business, intellectual property, technology, and international transactions. Jim is currently a partner at Klemchuk PLLC, a Dallas-based technology boutique law firm. He's also a Professor of Practice at SMU's Cox School of Business, teaching Entrepreneurial Law and Business Law. An entrepreneur himself, Jim has founded and co-founded several ventures, including VENTAC and Engage. His expertise spans law, education, and entrepreneurship.\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377967
location: Sign in to download the location
summary: CGEC Seminar: Founding & Funding with Jim Chester

description: Want to study abroad this summer and learn a critical language? No background experience is necessary for the fully-funded program sponsored by the State department!. . . . We will be hosting a CLS information session on Tuesday, October 24 at 12pm in the WLL Technology and Teaching Center (234 Clements Hall). . .  . . The application is now open for the 2024 Critical Language Scholarship (CLS) Program. The CLS Program is a funded program sponsored by the U.S. Department of State that provides intensive overseas language and cultural immersion and is open to U.S. students enrolled at Southern Methodist University.  Students can study one of 13 critical languages including: Arabic, Chinese, Hindi, Korean, Russian, Urdu, and more!. . . . If you want to chat about the CLS Program or other funded study abroad opportunities, contact Dr. Brandon Gray Miller (bgmiller@smu.edu) to arrange a time to meet.\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=378006
location: Clements Hall 234, ,

description: Each year, the Dr. Dennis Simon Civil Rights Pilgrimage offers the SMU community an opportunity to explore sites and meet people of the American Civil Rights Movement.  Highlighting the multi-disciplinary reality of social movements, we seek to inspire new advocates for human and civil rights as we learn from faith leaders and the lessons of non-violent social activism. Together we will learn about the work of peace and justice in the past and now. description: Storytelling – the newest old technique is back in the news. It’s not just the facts anymore. Stories build corporate culture, underlie the most persuasive sales efforts, and recruit new employees. The successful business executive and leader of tomorrow will need to understand how to strategically use stories and be a compelling storyteller. Howard Schultz, the founder of Starbucks, recently told Business Week that he was revamping Starbucks’ corporate culture to position it for new growth, and his chief tool was storytelling. This seminar looks at how a number of companies are using stories– some successful, some not-so-successful – as well as how the “new media” has helped companies “spread the word.” But, this technique also puts companies at risk as consumers tell their own stories. We will cover basic components of a story as well as sophisticated strategies for telling stories\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377936
location: Sign in to download the location
summary: Influencing through the Power of Storytelling

description: Almost two decades ago, Yoram sat with an organizational psychologist and asked, “am I a leader or an individual contributor?” The answer changed his professional life and career path forever (and for the better). Corporate America is obsessed with leadership. Everybody wants to rise in the organizational hierarchy, and we encourage it. But there is a cost for it. In this keynote, in an engaging, inspiring, sometimes humorous, and sometimes emotional and dead serious, Dr. Yoram Solomon will start by explaining why we are so obsessed with leadership, what are the true costs to the organization, one of which is how it devastates trust in the organization. He will continue and explain why not everybody should be a leader, and finish with a path forward to get there.\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377939
location: Sign in to download the location
summary: The Cost of Our Obsession with Leadership

description: Organized in collaboration with Armstrong Faculty in Residence Willie Baronet and our Engage Dallas cause, this is the fifth annual HOME IS A JOURNEY program. The event will begin at Doak Walker Plaza, first with the creation of blessing bags, free food and some announcements. Participants will then march across SMU campus while carrying signs created by those experiencing homelessness to Dallas Hall Lawn/Flag Pole area for the conclusion of the event. Representatives from student led organizations and others will share about how we can inspire positive change in our community. This event hopes to raise awareness and compassion for the issue of homelessness.. . . . Willie Baronet has been buying and collection homeless signs since 1993 as part of the long-term art project WE ARE ALL HOMELESS. A documentary film about this project, Signs of Humanity, is available on Amazon Prime. There is an exhibit of these signs, as well as portraits by Canadian photographer Leah den Bok on display in the Jordan Gallery in the Meadows School of the Arts through November 17, 2023.. . . . This event connects to our commons, to Engage Dallas, and to the greater campus and Dallas community. It brings awareness to our social issue of homelessness and brings together students, faculty and staff. description: At SMU, we recognize the power of collaboration. By forging connections with artists, educators, and advocates, we yield to the voices of the less fortunate to inform and bridge the gap between the lived experience, art, education, and community impact. Through the “HOME? Humanizing the Homeless: Portraits and Signs” art exhibit and the Home is a Journey March and Symposium, SMU empowers individuals to wield their creativity, scholarship, and action as a tool for change in pursuit of a just society.. . . . Panel One: Convergence of Compassion: Art, Homelessness, and Social Justice.. . Panel Two: Educating for Equity: Exploring Higher Education’s Role in Fostering Social Conscience in the Classroom.. . Panel Three: Trailblazers for Change: Non-Profit Leaders Working to Eradicate Homelessness and Inspire Social Justice.. . . . Description: . . The panel of experts on the intersection of art and social justice is a beacon of hope, casting light on a path forward where creativity and compassion intertwine to shape a more just and equitable world. Each panelist brings a unique blend of artistic prowess and a profound commitment to advocating societal equity. Each expert draws inspiration from interpreting struggles, triumphs, and the timeless beauty of the human experience. Their art mirrors society's complexities, encouraging dialogue and introspection and harmonizing the pursuit of justice and dignity for all.. . . . Moderator: Guadalupe Roman, Human Rights Students . . Speakers. . 1.\tWillie Baronet, M.A., M.F.A., Professor of Advertising, SMU, creator of We Are All Homeless and Signs of Humanity . . 2.\tRosie Frasso, PhD, SM, SM, CPH, Thomas Jefferson University . . 3.\tEddie Dunn, formerly homeless, advocate, speaker for homelessness. . 4.\tLeah den Bok, Photographer and creator of Humanizing the Homeless  . . Panel Two: Educating for Equity: Exploring Higher Education’s Role in Fostering Social Conscience in the Classroom. . . (2:00 – 2:50). . . . Description: . . In today’s rapidly changing world, higher education institutions play a pivotal role in shaping not only the academic knowledge of students but also their social conscience. This panel will examine how universities can effectively instill empathy, ethical responsibility, and civic engagement in their students. Through innovative teaching methods, curricular initiatives, and extracurricular activities, higher education can empower students to become active, socially conscious citizens committed to addressing pressing social challenges.. . . . Moderator: Celine Horner, Simmons graduate student (counseling) . . Speakers. . 1.\tLaura Robinson-Doyle, PhD, Professor in Applied Physiology and Sport Management, SMU. . 2.\tRick Halperin, PhD, Professor, Director of the Human Rights Program, SMU. . 3.\tMaria Dixon-Hall, PhD, Professor of Corporate Communication and Public Affairs, Senior Advisor to the Provost, Chief Diversity Officer, SMU. . 4.\tSheri Kunovich, PhD, Associate Provost for Student Academic Engagement and Success, SMU. . 5.\tStudent Advocate for Social Justice in the Classroom . . . . Panel Three: Trailblazers for Change: Non-Profit Leaders Working to Eradicate Homelessness and Inspire Social Justice.. . (3:00 - 3:50). . . . Description: . . This inspiring and informative panel discussion features visionary non-profit leaders on the frontlines of the battle against homelessness. This engaging panel brings together a diverse group of dedicated experts, each with unique insights and experiences, to explore the multifaceted challenges of homelessness and its broader social justice issues. . . *(Description is fluid and can change based on the participants). . . . Moderator: Koedi Nealy (SMU Student) . . Speakers. . 1.\tBill Holston, JD– COO for Dallas Eviction Advocacy Center  . . 2.\tJoli Angel Robinson – President and CEO: Housing Forward . . 3.\tDaniel Roby – CEO of Austin Street Center . . 4.\tDavid Woody, PhD - President and CEO: The Bridge. . 5.\tTamika Perry, CEO of Dallas Hope Charities. . . . . . Reception (4:00 – 4:30). . \n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=378191

description: Stress is inevitable in life, and college students experience different types of stress. Test anxiety is also common among college students, and can negatively affect your grades. But fear not! One of the best ways to decrease stress and test anxiety is to understand that some stress and anxiety is not only normal, it’s beneficial! We just have to manage it so that there isn’t too much.. . . . Attend this workshop to learn about what stress is, how it manifests, and how to recognize and make changes to decrease it. description: Join us for an exhilarating showcase of entrepreneurial talent at the SMU Business Accelerator Program's (BAP) 90-Second Elevator Pitch Event!. . . . 🚀 About the Event:. . Get ready to witness the energy, innovation, and creativity of our aspiring entrepreneurs as they distill their groundbreaking business ideas into a compelling 90-second pitch. These emerging innovators have been refining their concepts throughout the BAP program, and now they're ready to captivate you with their vision.. . . . 🌟 Why Attend?. . - Gain insights into the latest trends and innovations in entrepreneurship.. . - Discover potential investment opportunities.. . - Connect with motivated and talented entrepreneurs.. . - Be inspired by the future leaders of the business world.. . . . 👥 Who Should Attend?. . - SMU Students looking to join the BAP next year. . - Investors looking for promising ventures.. . - Mentors and professors seeking to connect with passionate entrepreneurs.. . - Entrepreneurs interested in networking and learning from peers.. . - Anyone intrigued by the exciting world of startups and innovation.. . . . 🎤 Pitch Format:. . Each participant will have 90 seconds to pitch their business idea to a panel of judges and the audience. Get ready for rapid-fire presentations that showcase the essence of each venture.. . . . 🏆 Prizes:. . Stay tuned to see who will take home the coveted prizes for the best pitches. Your presence could make all the difference!. . . . ⏰ Timeline:. . - 9:30 AM: Registration Opens. . - 10:00 AM: Competition Commences. . - 12:30 PM: Intermission for Judge Deliberation and Celebration with a Mimosa Bar and Pastries. . - 1:30 PM: Winners Revealed. . . . Don't miss out on this opportunity to be part of a dynamic event that celebrates entrepreneurship, innovation, and the next generation of business leaders. RSVP now and secure your spot at the BAP 90-Second Elevator Pitch Event!\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=377788
location: Crum Auditorium - In Collins, ,
summary: 🚀 SMU Business Accelerator Program: Elevator Pitch Competition

description: Join us for an informative orientation about volunteering at Medical City Dallas, where we will explore the essential aspects of volunteering and the values that drive their dedicated team. The event will take place in FOSC 153 on November 28th from 5-6 pm. The volunteer Coordinator from Medical City will inform students of the volunteering services that are provided. Including the various roles in the program During this event will familiarize ourselves with the principles of Volunteering care and learn how it focuses on enhancing the quality of life for individuals with life-limiting illnesses. Also, learn about the range of resources and emotional support we provide to families and caregivers.. . . . We will also partake in a volunteering role at the hospital in which we will make soup kits for discharged patients at the Day Surgery Unit. . . . . description: \t. . Join us at Perkins Chapel on Thursday, December 14 at 7pm for A Cool Yule Christmas Concert with The Light Crust Doughboys! The concert will be followed by a reception at Bridwell Library in the Gill Hall and Blue Room. This concert is free and open to the public for all to enjoy. We hope to see you there!. . . . Bridwell Library and The Light Crust Doughboys continue in 2023 as they present their annual gift to the community, a family Christmas concert series with a very special Light Crust Doughboys 2023 Deep Ellum Christmas Revue at SMU. This evening concert and reception has become a genuine Dallas family tradition celebrating Texas-style country-western music that The Light Crust Doughboys have been known for worldwide since 1931. In celebration of historic Deep Ellum Dallas' 150th anniversary, country-folk-western-cowboy traditions continue with the exciting addition of country blues, Christmas blues, and songs associated with the Doughboys and Deep Ellum. This Light Crust Doughboys Christmas concert will include an acoustic-unplugged set that recently debuted and was recorded live in Deep Ellum and covered by national news media. Bridwell Library presents an evening of music, history, and folk culture for the Christmas season 2023 to be remembered for years to come.   \n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=378739
location: Perkins Chapel, 6001 Bishop Blvd, Dallas, TX 75205, United States

description: Wrap up the semester with some warm drinks, cookies, and a game bound to make a few friends and enemies. Come participate in a game of White Elephant or simply come for refreshments.. . . . What is White Elephant?. . If you are unfamiliar or perhaps you know it by another name, White Elephant is a game of claiming and swapping surprise gifts. Each person brings a wrapped item and they take turns opening up new items or claiming a previously revealed item. At the end, everyone walks away with something!. . . . How will we play?. . Our game of White Elephant will be fun and lighthearted. Each participant will bring either a tree ornament or a fun desk item/toy. Ideally, you will bring the item wrapped but we will have some supplies if needed. Each item should be under $5.. . . . Instructions. . If you would like to participate, please be sure to complete the following. . • Select and wrap an ornament or desk display item/toy. . • On 12.19, bring your gift to HTSC 206. . • Show up for the fun at 3:00 PM\n---\nEvent Details: https://smu360.smu.edu/rsvp?id=378801
